title: A Little Devil in America: Notes in Praise of Black Performance
author: Abdurraqib, Hanif
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This one is more even than They Can't Kill Us Till They Kill Us, but I kind of like the rollercoaster-y unevenness of They Can't Kill Us more? Three tThis one is more even than They Can't Kill Us Till They Kill Us, but I kind of like the rollercoaster-y unevenness of They Can't Kill Us more? Three thoughts: 1) I've been contemplating feelings a lot lately. in "Board Up the Doors, Tear Down the Walls" Hanif touches on rage as a form of love. and how rollercoasteryness is sometimes better than being numb and centered. (this essay also feels like an extension of one in They Can't Kill Us.. which I can't reference by name because that book is in a box in a building I can't acces)2) I think the thing I like so much about Hanif Abdurraqib's work, unsurprisingly, is how he manages to be so damn soft and optimistic. Beef, and anger, and death are all opportunities for connection and love and turning into cgi bees. How and when can I see the world as he sees it?3) Early on in the whole book, in "On Marathons and Tunnels", an essay about Soul Train and Dance Marathons, Hanif puts together the best written description I've seen about partner dancing. It'll have better impact with the build up of the whole essay. and it's too unwieldy to block quote here. but you can't stop me. He starts this last image by saying that in the early days of Soul Train, there were few coordinated partners. and so often people in the Line would just have to figure it out on the spot together, as partners. He says, (view spoiler)[ “In these scenarios, there was no time to figure out choreography with someone, just those brief moments to lock eyes before being at the mercy of each other's movements. Then it was just the two of you, moving through a narrow tunnel of music and shouts urging you forward. ...And so the dancers must rely on what they know of the body to figure themselves —and each other —out of the hot, pulsating room, with nothing but noise and instinct to guide them before they reach the end of the line and part, maybe forever. “And I think this is how I would most like to imagine romance, friends, or should I say lovers. In praise of all my body can and cannot do, I wish to figure out how it can best sing with all of yours for a moment in a room where the walls sweat. I wish to lock eyes across a dance floor from you while something our mothers sang in the kitchen plays over speakers. I want us to find each other among the forest of writhing and make a deal. “Okay, lover. It is just us now The only way out is through.”  (hide spoiler)]...more

review: In her acknowledgements, Novik mentions in passing that her editor said the imagined readers of this would be in their thirties. (Hi, that’s me) I takIn her acknowledgements, Novik mentions in passing that her editor said the imagined readers of this would be in their thirties. (Hi, that’s me) I take that to mean this is Novik’s take on an updated or reimagined version of Hogwarts built on nigh a quarter century’s worth of fan fiction. It does read like Harry Potter fan fiction—we could easily swap in Draco for El and Harry for Orion. The static characters are very static and could essentially be Cho Chang and Parvati Patil and Blaise Zambini. But things Novik does well: pacing- never do I feel like she’s holding back because she’s waiting to reveal something: she creates problems, solves them and keeps it moving. She also hints at (and I want more of it) the system being rotten and hopefully we get to some dismantling rather than entrenching systems of power in books 2/3. As always, I appreciate 1) friendship being magic 2) wait, are we dating? 3)friendly neighborhood voids. ...more

title: How Democracies Die: What History Reveals About Our Future
author: Levitsky, Steven
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: See Kraz'  for more context- but this is a solid overview of the slide into autocracy in various forms by military coup and also the removal of See Kraz'  for more context- but this is a solid overview of the slide into autocracy in various forms by military coup and also the removal of democratic guardrails. To me, the most incisive point comes in the last 2-3 chapters. The compromise of 1877 was surely covered in my US History class (half a lifetime ago), but the echo of its legacy through the last century and a half wasn't quite so resounding until I read this. Our country's democracy was founded on defining blacks as not fully human to assuage white southerners. The compromise of 1877 which ended reconstruction and affirmed white supremacy for the sake of healing the nation's polarization post-civil-war set black rights back 150 years. And today. Today the onus is on us to not repeat history. To return to what Levitsky and Ziblatt name forbearance and mutual tolerance without compromising the rights and liberties of BIPOC....more

I picked up this book in the fall and set it down, and this time I finished it in one eveI feel like I've been rating everything four stars lately(?) I picked up this book in the fall and set it down, and this time I finished it in one evening. The best parts of this are when Emoni is musing about the conflicting aspects of her life: how to prioritize- how people see her, etc etc. This character in some ways shows how the privilege of having support and people believing in you is powerful in the face of a lot of hard circumstances. I think the actual action and interaction between characters feels stiff, unlike The Poet X. I love the different Boriqua narrators Acevedo has, how different they sound from each other.Cant wait to read more by her ...more
